{"ts":"2026-06-26T07:42:38.893Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Clarifying Navigation Logic**\n\nI've realized `CompanyNavigation` is a specialized header for subpages like `/company/contact`. This provides the selected subpage in mono-space. Now, I'm verifying if `/contact` is also a directly accessible page; ensuring the structure works holistically.\n\n\n**Consolidating Contact Pages**\n\nI've confirmed both `/contact` and `/company/contact` render the same upgraded design. Examining `app/contact/page.tsx` revealed it's a simple forwarder to `app/company/contact/page.tsx`. This presents an elegant solution: upgrading the contact page within `app/company/contact/page.tsx` will automatically update both `/contact` and `/company/contact`. This approach is clean, extremely DRY, and eliminates redundant code. The separate requirement check yielded no differences, so that is the strategy.\n\n\n**Designing Contact Page Layout**\n\nI'm now detailing the contact page structure. I'll use `InnerPageShell` and `CompanyNavigation` for consistency. The `InnerPageHero` will be customized with specific content: \"Enterprise Gateway\" category, \"Global Contact Protocol\" title, \"Protocol\" highlighted, and a description. An interactive pathway section will follow: a sidebar (desktop) or grid (mobile) for eleven pathways, each with icon, title, description, and indicator. Each pathway selection dynamically updates a premium contact form to the right, which will also need designing.\n\n\n**Crafting Form Dynamics**\n\nI'm now customizing the contact form pathways. I'm focusing on making each pathway's form feel distinct and professional. Each will have a unique title, form inputs, and simulated submission logic to show users how it'll work. I'm designing each form with a sleek, dark aesthetic: charcoal/black colors, neon borders, glowing grids, and custom hover effects. I'm also ensuring a custom status display, too. For instance, the \"Talk To Sales\" pathway includes fields for business email and platform, while \"Book Workshop\" focuses on execution mode and primary challenge.\n\n\n**Defining Contact Pathways**\n\nI'm expanding the contact form pathways to include several new options beyond the existing ones. These will be: \"Sandbox ID,\" with inputs for priority tier, environment context, and operational log details; \"Partnership\" with full name, partner organization, strategic alignment type and regional reach; \"Media\" with publication, representative name, business email, theme, and deadline; \"University\" with institution, investigator name, academic email and research domain; \"Investors\" with fund name, principal contact, business email and scope; and finally \"Careers\" requiring name, professional email, profile link and area of expertise. I'll maintain the dark design.\n\n\n**Designing Secure Login**\n\nI'm now focusing on the `/portal` page, which will serve as a secure client workspace preview. I've been instructed to create a placeholder login UI featuring SSO, passkey, or cryptographic token options. Before login, the design will show a \"Secure Enclave Entrance.\" The placeholder will also show all dashboard preview panels. I'm prioritizing a high-fidelity, secure design.\n\n\n**Developing Client Workspace**\n\nI'm now detailing the authenticated `/portal` workspace. After successful authentication (simulated), I'll build the client dashboard. This will show enclave details, like ID and status. A navigation bar will provide access to modules: \"Dashboard\" with sandbox summaries and links, \"Projects\" with deployment statuses, \"Programs\" with schedules, and \"Documents\" for zero-trust storage. The client workspace will be modular, and fully decoupled.\n\n\n**Expanding Workspace Modules**\n\nI'm now expanding the `/portal` modules with crucial data views. I'll add \"Invoices\" with invoice details and PDF downloads, \"Billing\" to detail subscriptions, and \"Approvals\" for audit logs. \"Support\" will offer secure tickets, and \"Analytics\" real-time compute metrics. I'll also add \"Governance\" for policy compliance and \"AI Operations\" to manage agents. Finally, a \"Control Center\" link will be added.\n\n\n**Refactoring Workspace Routes**\n\nI'm now streamlining the client portal. I've realized `/client` should render a tailored version of the secure workspace, avoiding code duplication. I'm focusing on the shared `ClientWorkspace.tsx` component for both `/portal` and `/client`. The same applies to the Control Center. This allows easy import and rendering across both `/portal/control-center` and `/client/control-center`.\n\n\n**Detailing Control Center Preview**\n\nI'm now detailing the `Control Center` layout. My focus is incorporating modules for \"Agent Health,\" \"Delivery,\" \"Spend,\" \"Adoption,\" and \"Governance.\" I am extremely pleased with the clean, elegant layout, eschewing fake data for high-fidelity, professional visuals.\n\n\n**Designing Control Center Details**\n\nI'm now detailing the `Control Center`'s interactive components. I'll make sure the breadcrumbs display as: \"Home / Client Portal / Control Center\". The top bar will show enclave details. The five preview modules will use either a tab-based or Bento-grid system. I'll make sure each module click opens a detailed log terminal, configurations, deployed agents, and protocols. I plan to use Framer Motion for premium, fast transitions.\n\n\n**Verifying Placeholder Parameters**\n\nI'm now verifying our use of frontend-only placeholder states to simulate backend behavior, focusing on technical, developer-centric parameters and realistic configuration text. I am also checking against the earlier constraints: ensuring the approved landing page hero and right-side video are retained.\n\n\n"}}
